</td><td valign=top bgcolor=d1c3b5 class=headings><font color=#000000>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/24/02 1:39:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Isharra's Story</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Flight from Felwithe</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
“You WILL marry him, Isharra!” roared her father, his flashing gray eyes warning of his thunderous anger. Jaryll Moonsong was a kind man, a gentle and loving father to his daughter. He was patient, considerate, and generous most of the time. Slow to anger, he chose the road of diplomacy before plunging into conflict. But on those rare occasions when his ire was raised, even his closest, most stalwart companions gave him wide berth. And right now, Isharra was at the center of the storm. <br>
<br>
Slamming her chamber door on his face, Isharra slid the bolt into place, tears streaming down her pale cheeks and pooling in the corners of her mouth. Collapsing with her back against the door, she tore the gaudy ruby baubles from her ears and threw them at the bureau leaning against the south wall of her room. The earrings clattered against the oak and then fell to the floor. “I will NOT!” Isharra screamed, now stepping on the rubies with all the force she could muster. “He is selfish and insensitive! Arrogant and rude! And he's SO skinny and he wears a DRESS for Tunare's sake, a DRESS!!” she spat, kicking the ruined earrings beneath her bed. <br>
<br>
On the other side of the door, Jaryll sighed deeply, pounding his fist once on the door. “Robes, daughter. He wears the robes of an enchanter. Isharra, what reason have you for such wicked words? Gareth has not once treated you poorly! He shows you nothing but kindness! Indeed, look at the gifts he lavishes upon you! Those ruby earrings! The gowns, the gems he has given you! And the betrothal ring! That ring could have paid for our entire estate! Has he ever spoken harshly to you? Nay! He LOVES you! He’s a good match for you---“ <br>
<br>
“Gaudy things, all of them! THINGS! THINGS! THINGS!” she growled, punctuating each word with a pound of her fist on the door. “The only reason I have them is because you undermined my desire to reject him by speaking for me!! You didn’t even----“ <br>
<br>
Jaryll’s voice boomed through the door, cutting her off. “I am your FATHER, Isharra, and I know what is best for you! It is my RIGHT to speak for you! You can’t live here with me for the rest of your life! You are of age! It’s time that you begin your own life now! What if I wish to take a wife, start anew? There cannot be two ladies of the household, especially not with you as stubborn as you are!” <br>
<br>
Isharra sobbed gently, lowering her face into her hands. She heard a shuffling outside as her father sat down, his back against the door. “Darling,” he said, his voice tender, “I only want what is best for you. Do you think I would allow you to marry someone who I thought would harm you? Gareth loves you. He and I have spoken at length about it. He has his rough edges, but so did I when your mother married me! I want you to be happy, and you WILL be, if you give him a chance. Please trust me, Isharra. Please.” <br>
<br>
“But I don’t love him, papa! No---I don't even <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>   like</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> him,” came her small voice through the door. <br>
<br>
“You will learn to, darling. I promise,” Jaryll replied tenderly, sensing surrender in his daughter’s voice. <br>
<br>
A sudden crash of something hitting the door proved his senses wrong. “I---<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>   crash</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->---will---<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>   crash</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->---not---<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>   crash</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->---marry---<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>   crash</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->—him!” she roared as a chair, a washbasin, a vase, a shoe, and anything else within arm’s reach gathered in a broken pile at the foot of the door. <br>
<br>
Isharra’s defiance only steeled his resolve, and Jaryll stood, brushing a patch of silver hair back from his brow, his mouth a tight line. “Yes, you will,” he said firmly, his voice strong and even. “It has already been arranged. I had hoped it would be a joyous occasion. Your mother would be ashamed of you, daughter.” With those last stinging words, he marched off. <br>
<br>
Isharra sagged to the floor, wiping tears from her emerald eyes, disbelieving her ears. Surely he was just bluffing, trying to scare her into obedience. Surely. But the next day a team of seamstresses arrived from House Crystalbrook, there to take measurements for the wedding gown of the bride of Lord Crystalbrook’s eldest son. And, like a zombie, Isharra let them poke and prod, present color swatches and patterns, just nodding dazedly at whatever was suggested. At one point, she mused aloud, &quot;Perhaps we should wear matching dresses. . .&quot;---only to feel the sudden prick of a pin in her backside. &quot;Oh my! Sorry, dear,&quot; the seamstress gushed, her voice as warm as a Halas night.<br>
<br>
The night before the wedding came too fast. And Isharra, finally jarred from her depressed resignation by a visit from Treewhisper, her sweet druid half-sister, snuck out of Felwithe with Treewhisper’s help. The druid spirited Isharra away for a brief respite in Surefall Glade, far from Felwithe and its obligations.<br>
<br>
After dedicating herself as a Priestess of Tunare in service to the Band of Dreamers, Isharra remained secretive about her flight from Felwithe, fearful that her father would get wind of her location. Some of the Dreamers were courtiers, and may have guessed her identity, but so far, thank Tunare, none of them had revealed that it was she, Isharra Moonsong, who had fled obligation and duty in Felwithe for a life of adventure. At least so far, she was free. <p><i>Isharra Moonsong</i><BR>
<i>Priestess of Tunare</i><br>
