*blushes and smiles knowingly* <p><i>Isharra Moonsong</i><BR>
<i>Priestess of Tunare</i><br>
<i>Proud Former Milkmaid of Felwithe</i><BR><a href="http://www.guildportal.com/guildHome.asp?GuildID=1158">Band of Dreamers</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 64<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/27/02 10:46:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Treewhisper's Tale</span><hr size=1> Sitting upon a stone, the skirts of her lilac robe spread daintily around her, Isharra gazes at the faces gathered around the fire. Old and young, warriors and healers alike have come to share a cup of cider and talk the night away in the safety of Surefall Glade. Every person at the fire has told a story, some so bawdy Isharra’s cheeks colored an alarming pink, prompting one worried druid to ask if she had fallen ill. No, she had replied, she would be fine in a moment. Finally her turn to tell a story is here, and after gazing at the stars for a moment, trying to choose her tale, she hears the sound of the wind whispering through the pines, and she knows immediately what she’ll share: <br>
<br>
“Some of you may know this tale, as a part of it takes place right here in this grove, but it is a tell worthy of telling and remembering. I wish to tell you the story of Treewhisper, my half-sister. Customarily, a High Elf would not admit to having siblings of questionable birth, but I say to the depths with custom! There is no other I would have as sister above Treewhisper. She is a creature of beauty and grace (though in a rustic sort of way, I confess.) <br>
<br>
“To begin, my mother, Elyandra, died of a cancer when I was still an elfchild. No, no... do not feel pity for me... I have long since recovered from her death and she is now a pleasant, warm memory. But for many, many years after her death, my father remained in mourning, taking no other in her stead. His love for her was boundless. <br>
<br>
“As some of you may know, my father ranks high in Felwithe court, and many beautiful Ladies sought to catch his eye--and failed. I was just young then, unaware of the intrigues of the court. Ah, how I long for such innocence again! <br>
<br>
“But I digress. My father met Moonmist, mother of Treewhisper, in Qeynos, when the moon was pregnant with its silver light. Magic was in the air, and later some said he was bewitched by the lovely druidess. Knowing Treewhisper as I do now, I think Moonmist's beauty was simply irresistible to my lonely father. Who knows for sure? Father won't speak of it. <br>
<br>
“Their love lasted only a few very passionate nights. When my father awoke, Moonmist was gone, and in her place remained only a small wooden carving of a great, gnarled tree. My father, confused and hurt, stored the carving away, not to be seen again for years upon years, until the day his eyes fell upon a wandering druid whose visage was almost so like Moonmist's that, for a moment, he thought her his lost love. But of that, I will speak another time. I wish now to relate to you the tragic tale of Treewhisper's lost wood. <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
“On a bed of verdant grass, sheltered by the knotted arms of a great ancient oak tree, Treewhisper took her first breath. The trees were the only midwives to attend the child's mother, and the wolves were the only family to pace anxiously along the edge of the misty grove. But as Moonmist gently cleansed the blood from her newborn babe, she knew that she'd have it no other way. The breeze sang through the trees, celebrating the birth of their Keeper's child. The soft susurrations of sound were whispers to Moonmist's ears. The trees were whispering the good news, one to the next throughout the wood: an heir to the forest was born. Moonmist rejoiced in their approval, calling the child Treewhisper in honor of her ancient wooded family. <br>
<br>
“As the child grew, Moonmist taught her the ways of the Woodmothers, instructing Treewhisper in the ancient magicks of life, renewal, and rebirth. Moonmist knew her time as the Keeper of Silverglade Wood was coming to an end, and Treewhisper would reign as Woodmother. The wood was small but cozy, needing only a single Woodmother as a guardian.<br>
<br>
“The child grew strong in body and wisdom, wolves her sisters and brothers, trees her guardians. Moonmist never mentioned Treewhisper's father, and Treewhisper never asked, for her mother had taught her that a Woodmother's forest was her husband, and her marriage bed, the grasses within. <br>
<br>
“Woodmothers do not die. Instead, they fade away into the nature that they protected for so long -- at least that's what the ancient lore of the Woodmother says. They say a Woodmother within her forest can last thousands of years as long as she dwells within its sheltering embrace, then her spirit simply transfers itself to the trees. Thus, each tree is a Woodmother of old, since the day when Tunare first appointed a Woodmother as guardian to a forest -- so they say. <br>
<br>
“So, Treewhisper was not surprised one day to find her mother's belongings in the small moss-covered cave that they called home. Moonmist's scrolls, herbs, battle gear, and personal belongings were all placed neatly together on the old, rock-carved shelf that lined the cave wall. This was not a sorrowful time for Treewhisper. <br>
<br>
“Though Tree, as she came to be called, would miss her mother's physical companionship, she could sense her in the wood and knew that it was as it should be. The wood was her kin now, its inhabitants her charges. The young Druid picked up the fine scimitar used by her mother over the ages and ran her finger along it's shining, sharp blade. She turned it in her hand. The balance fit her; no more practicing with old rusty scimitars in the glade with her mother. This weapon was meant for a woman, for a fighter, for a true defender of the forest. A soft smile touched Tree's face as she caught her reflection in its long steel blade. She had not realized how much she had grown. Her face looked somehow older. In place of merry, rounded cheeks, were cheekbones chiseled from tan clay. Instead of the dancing glow of innocence in her bark-colored eyes, she saw the wisdom of ages sparkling there--her mother's wisdom, passed down from mother to daughter. <br>
<br>
“And all was well in Treewhisper's corner of the realm -- for a time. Gnolls began invading the wood from the South, killing the wolves for meat and slashing and burning the trees. Treewhisper fought bravely for as long as she could. The Keepers of Jaggedpine Forest tried to send aid, but they had their own battles to fight as Gnolls invaded Surefall Glade. <br>
<br>
“The attacks became more frequent, the fires more encompassing, until Treewhisper was captured and imprisoned in Blackburrow. She felt the pain of the trees as they burned, and even from this far she heard their silent screams in her heart. And she could do nothing. She had failed her wood. She no longer heard its whispers, she no longer felt its presence. <br>
<br>
“Her wood was dead. <br>
<br>
“Not long after the destruction of Silverglade, Treewhisper found herself rescued by brave rangers sent from Surefall Glade. There was no rejoicing; Treewhisper had nowhere she wished to go, nothing to call home. Her will was to die in Blackburrow, for a Woodmother without her wood surely dies. <br>
<br>
“But Tunare works in strange ways. The inhabitants of Surefall Glade nursed her back to health, and the presence of the sheltering pines soothed some of her pain. Though her anguish ran deep, she was soon able to leave the Glade in search of her homeland, Kelethin, and in search of answers to the questions she had about her people. And she found those answers... but that, my friends, is a story for another time.”<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p><i>Isharra Moonsong</i><BR>
<i>Priestess of Tunare</i><br>
