<br>
I met with Cronadan today, as I wanted to learn more of his tale, to help me understand better the events that would cause a Teir'Dal to be hated in Neriak and accepted everywhere else. This is a scholarly pursuit for me, simply knowledge to add to my collection of anomalies that do not conform to my values.<br>
<br>
We spoke at length. He is an intriguing soul, and I felt like a child when I compared my petty little concerns to the things he has faced in his life. I will not scribe all the details of our conversation here, as I will simply have to repeat it again when I delve into my scholarly work later. But I will say this: I believe  his story. Perhaps there is one honorable Teir'Dal in all of Norrath, and this is he. <br>
<br>
Each day I learn new things that challenge all I have believed all my life. It is thoroughly exciting but frightening to me. <br>
Are we just the sum of all that we've been taught? Or are we more?<br>
<br>
Bah. Time for rest. Aluve, little book, aluve. <p><i>Isharra Moonsong</i><BR>
<i>Priestess of Tunare</i><br>
<i>Proud Former Milkmaid of Felwithe</i><BR><a href="http://www.guildportal.com/guildHome.asp?GuildID=1158">Band of Dreamers</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 81<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/2/02 8:58:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Isharra's Journal #5: The Bitter Taste of Humiliation</span><hr size=1> Isharra opens her journal, glad to have found it with her things, but distressed that it wasn't where she remembered putting it. After seeing everything in order, she scans the previous night's entry, a description of a dream, then tears it out, tossing the balled up parchment onto the fire. <br>
<br>
She watches the paper flare up and dissolve into ashes, then, satisfied, she begins to write: <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
Dear little book, <br>
<br>
Tonight I played the fool. At the urging of others, I tossed aside my values and breeding and tried to &quot;think out of the box,&quot; as they say. The result was my humiliation and degradation. I will never allow myself to do so again. <br>
<br>
I cannot afford the luxury of emotion. &quot;What was I thinking?&quot; I wonder now, looking back on my pathetic, emotional self. I am an embarrassment to myself and my family. I may not wish to marry Gareth, but from now on I will remember to behave as a Felwithe Lady and not some common tavern wench moon-eyed over a soldier. <br>
<br>
I am almost so ashamed of my own behavior tonight that I feared to pen this, for I'm not sure if I wish to be reminded of my folly again. But remember I must, for only by remembering this bitter taste of humiliation will I be able to avoid it in the future. <br>
<br>
On a more positive note: I have found a forever-friend in Bryer Thourne. I count that as a high point in a day gone awry. <br>
<br>
Now I must bathe. My hair is caked with blood and dirt and my robes are filthy with stains. The City of Mist is actually quite beautiful if you can avoid the beasts that haunt the passageways. I'll cloak myself from the undead and bathe in that delicious-looking waterway before making my camp. Yes, I am camped in the middle of the City of Mist, away from prying eyes and unwelcome guests, and safe from the creatures that roam as well. I like it here. Its dark, empty passageways make me feel right at home. <p><i>Isharra Moonsong</i><BR>
<i>Priestess of Tunare</i><br>
<i>Proud Former Milkmaid of Felwithe</i><BR><a href="http://www.guildportal.com/guildHome.asp?GuildID=1158">Band of Dreamers</a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A> at: 7/2/02 5:11:05 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 86<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/3/02 9:24:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Duty</span><hr size=1> The night was like a furnace, and the warm rain pattering against Isharra's bare arms and face was comforting.  She sat concealed in a tree outside of Felwithe, feeling more like her druid sister Treewhisper than a Lady, her vision of the beautiful stone and marble entryway blurred by tears. The branches of her leafy perch bowed under the weight of the rain, mimicking the way her heart now felt beneath its many burdens. Tomorrow she would return to Felwithe, not secretly, like she had these many months, but in plain view, with what little pride she she had left fueling each step. She would return to the home of her Father, beg his forgiveness. By the end of the week, her wedding plans would be back in motion, and by the end of the month, she would be Isharra Crystalbrooke. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   A small price to pay,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> she tried to tell herself. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   This is what I was raised to do; this is who I am.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A> at: 7/3/02 12:07:14 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/3/02 10:18:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Note for Cronadan</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Note: Isharra's views regarding Cronadan do NOT reflect the Band of Dreamers in any way, shape, or form. For this storyline, I have removed Isharra from the Band to ensure that no one associates the Band with grouping with evils or befriending evils---even though I do not consider Cronadan evil. What my character does here should be perceived as her own thoughts and feelings and should not in any way be associated with the Band of Dreamers. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Dear Cronadan,<br>
<br>
Vendui'. Forgive me for my brutal treatment of you this evening last. You were a friend to me when others did not even know I pained, and for that I thank you. There is indeed nobility and goodness in you, no matter what others say. You have proven yourself time and time again to be the antithesis of all that is Teir'Dal, and you will forever hold a place of respect in my heart. Now, the bad news: I have chosen to return to Felwithe in the morning and beg forgiveness of my father. I will submit to his will and within the month, I will be Isharra Crystalbrooke. The reason I pen this missive is that of all my friends, and I do call you friend, only my relationship with you will be affected by my marriage.  Others can come to my estate for visits, and my husband and Lord will not question my time spent with them. <br>
<br>
But, alas, you will never be welcome by my father, nor by my husband's family. This grieves me, for after I am wed, I may never see you again. I would like to spend some time with you prior to my wedding to finish my scholarly inquiry into your unique turning from darkness. It will have to be far from Faydwer, lest I be discovered. I will make some excuse to my father and betrothed for my brief absence---perhaps a few days---complete my studies and return home for my wedding. I ask that you consider my request. If you agree, please suggest places where I could spend a few days in anonymity, enjoying my last month of freedom with a friend I may never see again.<br>
<br>
Bel'la dos,<br>
Isharra <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A> at: 7/3/02 12:46:13 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucronadan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cronadan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/3/02 6:02:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Flight from Felwithe</span><hr size=1> Vendui Isharra,<br>
<br>
       I have often said that life is a constant challenge.  There are obstacles to overcome, mistakes to be made, and paths to choose.  I am happy to hear that you have made a decision as to what direction your life will go, though it pains me to know that I may lose your friendship, outwardly anyway.  Whether or not I am allowed to visit you at your estate is of no consequence to me.  You are abbil.  If you are in Felwithe, Kelethin, Kaladim, Rivervale, it matters not to me, for I carry our friendship in my heart.  All I need to do is to look inside myself, and you will be there.  Just as you once told me that I have touched you, you have touched me as well.  You are one of two Koada'dal nobles that look upon me with kindness, and I will never forget our friendship.<br>
<br>
     Xas, I would like to talk with you before your marriage.  There are many places we could meet.  I am accepted in almost all of the light cities, so there should be little difficulty setting up a time and place for our discussions to continue. (I will send you a tell in game.)  I hope to meet with you soon.  Aluve Isharra.<br>
<br>
Yours in Everlasting Friendship,<br>
<br>
Cronadan Do`Bluth<br>
Renegade Velg'larn<br>
Protector of the Kejekans<br>
Member of Twilight Bastion    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/4/02 8:29:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Shades of heart-break</span><hr size=1> Isharra sat in a velvety high-backed chair, her fingers working furiously on the embroidery in her lap. Her emerald gaze was fixed on her work, but unseeing, as Gareth sat watching her, an amused smile playing upon his thin lips. Books lined the walls of the parlor in the Moonsong estate, and Isharra had come to love its shelves full of wisdom and adventure, but right now the high stacks seemed to be closing in on her, crushing her. <br>
<br>
&quot;My lovely Isharra,&quot; Gareth said, his voice full of musing. &quot;So beautiful, with a spine of iron. Are you pleased to be home?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, my Lord,&quot; she replied, her eyes never leaving the embroidery. It wasn't really a lie. Of the choices available, this seemed the most pleasing.  She felt his eyes studying her and she felt her face pinken.<br>
<br>
&quot;What did you do out there, my Isharra? Did you battle dangerous foes, lead armies into battle? Play the damsel in distress?&quot; he mused, his voice low and biting.<br>
<br>
&quot;I served Tunare, my Lord,&quot; she replied, ignoring the bile rising in her throat. &quot;That is all. No more, no less.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah  yes, Tunare!&quot; replied the agnostic enchanter, his mockery barely disguised. &quot;Of course, my dear. How noble of you.&quot;<br>
<br>
The cleric's emerald eyes blazed at that and her head snapped up, her nostrils flaring as she tried to contain her anger. Gareth's face split in a grin and he laughed loudly, harshly. &quot;Oh dear, I've angered you. So sorry, of course. I should be overjoyed that the wench has brought you back to me, if she were not part of the reason you left to begin with. Forgive me, Isharra, but I am in no mood for pleasantries after having awakened to find my bride missing on the morning of my wedding. Did you even think of your father? His shame? Not to mention my own. What were you thinking?&quot; The heat rose in his voice and he smacked the embroidery from her hands, glaring as he cupped her chin and looked into her eyes, his face a finger's breadth from hers. &quot;Or perhaps you weren't thinking at all. Is that emptiness I see in your eyes? Perhaps air between those pretty ears?&quot;<br>
<br>
Isharra was stunned, her skin crawling with fear. He had never, ever been this way before. He had been arrogant, yes, but always tender and eager to please. Who was this man?<br>
<br>
He left go of her jaw, leaving a dull ache there, and began to pace. His shoulders hunched as he sighed, the anger seeming to succumb to sorrow. &quot;I love you, Isharra. You've known that for long and long. Why did you leave me?&quot; Was his voice breaking? Was that glisten in his eyes tears? Isharra felt a sudden wave of pity for him and she went to him, taking his hand gently.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm so sorry,&quot; she whispered, ashamed that she had brought this arrogant, self-assured elf noble to this state. He had every right to be angry, and that was surely all this was---the ravings of a broken heart. <br>
<br>
He looked up through his tears and lifted a hand to stroke her cheek. His pale hair looked like spun silk in the firelight. He was handsome and gregarious, with many friends among the court at Felwithe. Serving as his wife might not be so bad after all.<br>
<br>
Then the blue of his eyes suddenly froze over and his caress became rough. &quot;I'll not be shamed again, Isharra,&quot; he growled, then turned and left.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A> at: 7/4/02 8:30:47 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/udeneteth1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Deneteth1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_ball.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Seeker of Truth</span><br>  Posts: 245<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/8/02 11:09:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://deneteth.freeservers.com/image/den2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Shades of heart-break</span><hr size=1> Deneteth is thinking back to that day in the City of Mist when Isharra announced she was going back to Felwithe and her destiny.<br>
<br>
&quot;Politicians&quot; he said suddenly with a nuance of anger, disturbing the study of other scholars in the vast library of Sanctu Seru.<br>
<br>
At least she'll have plenty of time to go venture in the wilderness or take a true lover to her couch since he'll be busy roaming the corridors of the King's castle all days long.<br>
<br>
&quot;Politicians...&quot; he said again, shaking his head.<br>
<br>
And with this last word Deneteth went back to his study of the ancient Norrathian civilizations.<br>
<br>
Den <p><center>
