</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 104<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/8/02 1:49:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Isharra's Journal #6: Social Butterfly</span><hr size=1> Hello little book,<br>
<br>
It has been a few days since we last &quot;spoke,&quot; if speaking is what indeed we do. Father has been so affectionate lately, hugging me and caressing my cheek at every turn, so proud he is that I will soon be wife to a Crystalbrooke. You'd think that *he's* the one getting married. Nevertheless, it is good to have him near. Gareth has been busy with his duties at the palace for the past few days, so I've been able to spend time with my father, like when I was younger. We pore over old books and discuss the latest trends at court and even played dice for gold pieces the other night. Of course, he always returns my lost gold, but I keep his! <br>
<br>
What can I say about my future husband? I fear to tread there, to tell the truth. He's very kind and indulges me when he's getting his way. When he's not . . . I just don't know. I saw a side of him the other day that shocked me and frightened me a little. But then, I did embarrass his family (and my father) by my own waywardness, so I should count my self fortunate that Gareth will even still marry me. I learned yestermorn that my considerable dowry was going to be claimed by the Crystalbrookes, whether or not I came back from my adventures. They claimed they had rights to it for all their trouble, and Father, of course, agreed in his shame. Father was worried that it would make me unmarriagable, as he cannot afford another dowry fit for a Felwithe Lady. <br>
<br>
Father and Gareth seem to get along just grandly. No wonder---Gareth dotes on him and constantly indulges him when he has the mind to go on and on about his former military exploits. And Lord Crystalbrooke and Father were friends during his soldiering days, so that tie, too, binds he and Gareth together.  Well, I should leave you now, little book. I'm supposed to attend a social at the palace tonight. Oh joyous day. Bleh. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A> at: 7/10/02 6:47:23 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/9/02 9:35:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=326.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Face of the Goddess</span><hr size=1> Dearest Mother, please help me in this time of decision. My heart is broken, and my spirit weak.Oh Mother, please give me guidance that only a Mother can give. I am your humble servant.<br>
<br>
I penned this in your honor:<br>
<br>
Lovely maiden Chastity,<br>
Skin like silk and taut with youth,<br>
Your colors are many and celebrated.<br>
Tan like autumn leaves are you, or<br>
 black like onyx, chocolate brown,<br>
pale like sand, or red like cherry--<br>
you are the face of the Goddess.<br>
Remind me of my beauty, fair maid,<br>
remind me that I once wore your face<br>
and will someday again. <br>
<br>
Imbue me with your spirit, oh Mother, <br>
bless me with your Sight, <br>
for your eyes see all clearly--<br>
your eyes of amber, amethyst, or jade,<br>
obsidian, lapis, or sard, <br>
shaped like almond, egg, or diamond, <br>
the eyes of every Mother of every Child<br>
through all eternity are yours. <br>
<br>
Teach me to be kind, oh Mother,<br>
Instruct me in courage to protect those I love; <br>
give me spear, give me shield, give me cunning, <br>
So that none shall harm my little ones.<br>
Dwell within me, Love Eternal,<br>
shelter the life that springs from my womb,<br>
for we are Mothers, you and I.<br>
<br>
Prepare me for that day, oh Crone,<br>
That day when my hair, once lush, grows gray<br>
like the bare, resting trees of autumn,<br>
When my years remaining number less than lived,<br>
when my beauty, once vibrant, has taken new form.<br>
You are my friend, oh Ancient One--<br>
my dear, old friend, my Goddess.<br>
You have waited all this time for me,<br>
and now we finally meet, <br>
rheumy eyes of mine to yours eternal.<br>
Your many faces, oh Crone and seer,<br>
seem not so different now: <br>
Time-carved pathways of wisdom decorate<br>
each visage beneath a silvery crown. <br>
Dark-skinned or light, eyes of bark or sea,<br>
time touches all, without discrimination. <br>
Oh, Ancient One of night, <br>
prepare me for my sleep; <br>
prepare me for my final hours--<br>
I am tired now; my life is full. <br>
I wish to walk with you, oh Crone, <br>
to walk with you and hold your hand,<br>
I wish to walk with you in twilight<br>
on this winter day.<br>
I wish to walk and share my thoughts, <br>
my dearest hopes, my memories.<br>
I wish to dress with you in silver <br>
to match the stars that grace the sky--<br>
the silent, black, and ancient sky<br>
that hovers o'er the snow.<br>
<br>
Your face is hidden, Mother--<br>
the sky is dark, the moon is lost. <br>
Will you walk with me, my friend?<br>
The snow conceals familiar paths.<br>
<br>
Ah! To see your face in bloom, again,<br>
young and firm and bright! <br>
But walk with me for now,<br>
 gray and wrinkled as we are,<br>
Walk with me for now,<br>
as we've walked for these years past.<br>
And we'll walk until our footprints<br>
 in the snowfall are no more. <br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
